en_content:
AGI - President Donald Trump called on the Alien Enemies Act of 1798 to quickly deport alleged members of the Venezuelan gang Tren de Aragua (TdA), designated by the United States as a terrorist organization. Despite an order by federal judge James Boasberg > which temporarily blocked such deportations, the administration expelled more than 230 individuals to El Salvador>.&nbsp;
But in addition to the news, which has already made more than one eyebrow, is the video of deportation, circulated by Salvadoran president, Nayib Bukele>, who raised more than one criticism and much indignation. The film toured the world for the brutality and violence of the soldiers against the deported, taken by a plane and then led into a safe prison. Bukele underlined cooperation with the Trump administration in the fight against organized crime, ignoring the criticisms received.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> An antiquated law working as a pretext
There are many editorials, which have appeared in newspapers around the world, which emphasize how Trump uses this very old law, out of time, to justify the expulsion of people without a regular process and thus speeding up times and ways.
This action has aroused legal and humanitarian concerns, since the Alien Enemies Act> is historically associated with specific war periods and deals with national security issues in situations very different from those living in the United States. Trump relaunched the video by feeding further discussions on the operation.
Also because the phrase that accompanies everything, well visible on Truth>, cites the people of the gang as "moisters sent to our country by corrupt Joe Biden and radical left-wing democrats". &nbsp;
